Multiple sclerosis: it is not only the drugs that matter, but also the patient's will to fight.
Multiple sclerosis is a complicated disease, and a person with this diagnosis needs the care of a number of specialists: a neurologist, a physiotherapist, an occupational therapist, a urologist, an ophthalmologist, a psychologist, a psychiatrist and many other specialists.
However, it is not only about medical care, for example, women with multiple sclerosis also need consultations, if they decide to have a child, the care of these patients includes social and legal counseling, recommendations for housing modification, etc.
Still, all this is not enough: the development of the disease can be fundamentally affected by the patient himself.
The more he actively fights the disease, the longer he can work and does not have to fundamentally change the style of his life.
As doctors point out, the passivity of patients frees up space for the activity of the disease.
For example, it is proven that regular movement greatly delays the time when the patient needs some compensatory aid, for example, a stick.
It is important that patients and their surroundings do not submit to various myths, for example, that the disease automatically leads them to end up in a wheelchair.
That is why the Dej chance page (www.bezmytu.cz) was created, which is supported by the ongoing media campaign Give Yourself a Chance.
The most important person in the care of a patient with multiple sclerosis is a neurologist.
In multiple sclerosis, twice the adage applies that the sooner the disease begins to be treated, the more likely the doctor may affect something.
This is because we have multiple sclerosis drugs at an inflammatory stage when the process of neurodegeneration is not yet so strong.
The sooner we intervene, the greater the hope that we will be able to stop the disease and delay disability, explains Dr. Eva Medová from the Neurology Clinic of the General University Hospital in Prague.
It is very important in people with multiple sclerosis rehabilitation care, which most often solves the weakening of the lower limbs or balance disorders.
Patients are treated according to their individual needs: to maintain fitness, improve walking, strengthen the pelvic floor, relieve swallowing disorders or improve coordination.
"It's really individual, it depends on the specific difficulties of the patient," says MUDr. Martina Kövári, Chief of the Department of Rehabilitation and Physical Medicine of the University Hospital in Motol.
People with multiple sclerosis suffer from the same disease, but it manifests itself in everyone in a slightly different way.
Rehabilitation cannot stop the disease, but it can always relieve its symptoms.
However, physical activity also strengthens the immune state of the body, which is desirable in the case of multiple sclerosis.
Another positive of regular exercise is the fact that the sick verify what they can do, and this strengthens their confidence.
"Endorphins are also flushed out during exercise and a person feels good after it," PhDr points out. Kamila Řasová from the Department of Rehabilitation Medicine of the University Hospital Royal Vinohrady.
By affecting the physical side, we act on the limbic system responsible for emotions.
We directly interfere with the psyche and immune processes and stabilize the disease, he adds.
"Previously, these patients were so-called saved, today we know they need a targeted burden," says prof. PaedDr. Pavel Kolář, Head of the Department of Rehabilitation and Physical Medicine of the University Hospital in Motol.
The goal of physiotherapy is to keep one from being self-sufficient for as long as possible, including job title.
Therefore, physiotherapists cooperate with occupational therapists so that each person receives a compensatory aid tailored to him.
Many patients also need the care of a psychologist or psychiatrist.
They're in a difficult life situation.
When a serious illness comes into your life, it usually shakes people.
They experience shock, panic, fear.
They have to respond to a big burden - a loss of health.
With such a sore soul, we are to go to someone, not trying to carry everything on our own shoulders.
"I work with them so that they eventually come to the conclusion that even with a disability it is possible to live a full life and that multiple sclerosis does not mean the end of life," says psychotherapist Renata Malinová - Schubertová from the Neurology Clinic of the General University Hospital in Prague.
Without the Prague manufacturer Latecoere, airbuses would not fly.
Aviation production is synonymous with precision and advanced technologies.
The new aircraft are full of titanium or light and solid composite materials, which can not be manufactured and processed.
Still, in addition to super-precision, computer-controlled machine tools, in addition to autoclaves for shaping composites, you can come across something as ordinary as apricot stones.
In the drum, which resembles a pot of cotton candy, the edges of the sheet metal parts that have just come out of the milling machine are tumbled in a pile of stones.
"So far, no one has found anything better," smiles Ivan Dubský, CEO of air door manufacturer Latecoere Czech Republic.
In the area in Prague Letňany, the former Letov produces complete doors for the Airbus A320.
They are the only ones in the world to supply the door for the Brazilian Embraer 170.
Passengers entering the first and upper class on the upper decks of the world's largest airliner, the Airbus A380, also enter the door, part of which is assembled in Prague.
There are also doors full of composites for the new Boeing 787 Dreamliner.
Precision is the main motto here.
For example, the company has the moment keys adjusted twice a year.
If the yellow sticker lacks a record of inspection, they should explain in the Prague plant to the auditors from Airbus or Boeing, who regularly drive to see if the door is made according to the agreed rules.
However, the advanced technology has not yet completely replaced the human senses.
There are 1500 rivets on one door to the A320.
You have to shake the riveters by hand.
It takes them two days.
Even according to the sound of the impacting hammer, they will know if the rivet is already properly shaken.
The tolerance in which they move is minimal.
The rivet can rise above the surface of the aircraft from zero to 0.13 millimeters.
That's roughly twice the thickness of a human hair.
During the inspection, it is the turn of the trained touch.
When the controller runs his finger over a row of rivets, he can tell if any are out of tolerance.
Then he picks up the exact handler.
Letov fed the program of the training military aircraft L-39 before 1989.
In 1991, however, not a single one was produced.
The company quickly had to find new orders.
It was then put together with European aircraft manufacturer Airbus.
She won a tender for an emergency door supplier for the A321.
The courtship with Boeing was not so happy.
"We were a small company for them at the time, which did not have enough money for investments and for Boeing to guarantee long-term stable deliveries," Dubský recalls.
The door to the American manufacturer would have been slammed if Letov had not impressed the French group Latecoere at the Prague conference of the international aviation industry association in 1999.
I was talking about our cooperation with Airbus.
The next day, negotiations with the French started, Dubsky says.
A year later, Latecoere bought the Czech company and with a strong company came new orders.
In 2000, the installation of parts of the door for the A320 started.
Three years later, the door of the upper deck for the A380 was added.
In 2006, the company built a new composite processing hall for deliveries for Boeing Dreamliner.
Without Latecoere, we wouldn't have gotten to these big contracts ourselves.
Maybe we'd do parts or small parts.
The partners want a guarantee of supplies for twenty or thirty years, explains Dubský.
Last year, the Czech Latecoere achieved a turnover of more than 2.9 billion and profit after tax 147 million crowns.
The exclusive position among suppliers of aircraft manufacturers is not free.
Latecoere has invested 1.5 billion crowns in Prague since 2000.
The company must have quality certificates, certification of 170 special production processes and qualification cards for key employees.
Without them, the company would not produce any aircraft doors.
Obtaining certificates that the production processes correspond to the requirements of the customers and in repeated inspections to keep them costs, according to Dubský, millions of crowns.
Production processes change every year.
They are more accurate and stricter.
We have to train employees, retrofit the equipment and certify the whole process again, adds Dubský.
Now the company is finalizing the preparation of a process for zinc and nickel plating, which will replace the existing harmful cadmium for human health.
They received the assignment from the manufacturer, but then they had to adapt the technology for the equipment or chemicals they use in Prague.
The people of Boeing will come, check the concept of the entire line.
Then we'll show them the production.
They'll check our lab, too.
They test one set of samples themselves in their laboratory and then compare the results with ours, approaching the Dubsky way in which customers check them.
The reward is the Prague company long-term exclusive contracts.
With the Prague plant today, the production of embraos is and is falling.
For the A320, it produces half of the total volume of the door.
Replacing the Czech Latecoere is either impossible or very difficult for a Brazilian or European manufacturer.
However, this does not mean that he can say any price at the door.
The contract includes a price curve.
It indicates how much one door will cost after ten, fifty, hundreds of pieces made.
The price per piece still drops to a certain limit value.
We have to fit into this price pattern.
If we don't, we'll lose, says Dubsky.
Half of the hall where the electric cabinets for the military Airbus A400 M are assembled is still empty.
It is a symbol of the future.
Behind the screen, a new semi-robotic line for riveting and installation of doors for the innovative A320 Neo is being built.
Riveting will speed up and refine.
"This is the trend that is taking assembly in aviation," adds Dubský.
The sale has a future line secured.
Airbus reports that airlines have so far ordered 3278 units of the new A320.
Just a few meters next to it, a line will be created for the complete installation of doors for the A380 upper deck.
It is a strategic decision of our parent company.
The goal is to reduce production times and reduce costs.
Full assembly could begin within two years, Dubsky says.
Before that, however, the company must pass the qualification tests, for example, for the installation of some electrical and electronic equipment in the door for the largest Airbus.
The company is also betting on the further development of production from composite materials.
In addition to Boeing, it should also participate in the new Airbus A350 program, which will compete with the American Dreamliner.
"It's a huge credit for the company when it can process composites in addition to metal materials," says Dubský proudly.
However, Latecoere is on the edge of production capacity in the Czech Republic.
There is no other place in the Letov area where it is located.
Before the entry of the French mother, the company had 180 employees.
Now he has 800, and within three years there could be a hundred more.
As long as Airbus and Boeing are competing to see how many new planes the airline orders each year, they may not be worried about their jobs.
Although it has contracts for several years in advance, the parent company of Prague’s Latecoere faced a threat of bankruptcy.
The French group did not have enough money for September's loan payments.
In the end, Latecoere was able to reach an agreement with the main creditors.
At the end of August, part of the loans were exchanged for shares.
Creditors gained a 37.4 percent stake in the company by raising capital by 57.4 million euros.
The company's debt fell by two-thirds, or 180 million euros.
The second part of the financial recovery came in early September.
