“Sonogenetics” or control of brain cells by means of sound waves
This video shows how sound impulses affect the direction in which the nematodes move.
The researchers raised worms with a genetically modified nervous system that can control sound waves.
The small nematodes change direction when they are struck by sound impulses that are inaudible to the human ear.
The pulses work by switching the cells of genetically modified motor neurons that are programmed to respond to these ultrasonic waves.
Related: Scientists can read and write brain activity using light
The researchers said these worms are a great example of a new methodology called sonogenetics, which uses ultrasound to activate brain, heart and muscle cells and activates outside the body.
Sreekanth Chalasani, a researcher at the Salk Institute in La Jolla, California, told the Guardian that the method could one day replace deep brain stimulation - an invasive procedure in which electrodes that stimulate the brain are injected into the patient's brain. The method is used, for example, to treat the symptoms of Parkinson's disease.
The nematodes usually do not respond to ultrasound, but Chalasani has found that the reaction occurs when they are placed in a fluid containing microscopic bubbles.
As he found, bubbles amplify ultrasonic waves, which then pass through the body of worms.
Reinforced ultrasonic waves act in the ion channels of TRP-4, which are found in the membranes of some worm cells.
Thanks to the sound waves, these channels open and activate the cells they are associated with, according to a report by the journal Nature Communications.
In order to control the nematodes using ultrasonic waves, Chalasani genetically modified the worms so that some of their motor neurons contain the tRP-4 ion channels.
When he then applied ultrasound to such modified worms, the sound waves were amplified by microbubbles and transferred to the worms, where they turned on the modified motor neurons.
The new method in many ways resembles optogenetics, a pioneering tool that allows scientists to turn on and off neurons using light.
But Chalasani said sonogenetics could have many advantages over this technique.
Unlike light, which must be sent by optical fiber to the desired location in the brain, ultrasonic waves can penetrate the tissue without restriction and be sent directly to the brain.
"We believe that when we use gene therapy and therapeutic viruses, we can target human neurons and make them temporarily sensitive to ultrasound signals used in clinical treatment to treat neurological diseases," Chalasani said.
He added that the method would also find its application in the treatment of insulin-producing muscle cells and cells.
