The symbol of the village has come to life.
The wheel of the windmill above Chlum is spinning again after years.
It can be seen by far because it is located on a fifteen-meter-high mast.
People from around the country call him "the fan on Chlum."
For the village with 150 inhabitants, it became even one of the elements of the municipal emblem, which the municipality gained on the occasion of the meeting of natives in 2010.
"We applied for a sign at the time and of course we wanted to have a fan on the emblem, everyone knows it in the vicinity," said the mayor Jiří Mašek.
The Chlum wind pump is a local technical monument.
It is also a memento of the present: it reminds us of a time when people here fought for quality drinking water.
The one in Chlum in the past centuries was a rarity.
It was not until 1910 that the Chlum councillors decided on a solution that then suited until the mid-1980s.
In the village at the turnoff to Číchov, they had a seven-meter-deep well excavated.
Three years later, the well was complemented by a metal structure with a wind pump, which pumped water into the reservoir at the highest point of the village, near the local church.
"The construction was carried out by the company Antonín Kunc from Hranice in Moravia with a cost of 2 400 crowns," states the commemorative inscription on the ground-floor fence of the structure of the mast.
The pump after several repairs and falls of the wind wheel served in 1971.
On May 7, 1973, a new chapter began to be written on the fight for water: that day a new water supply began to serve in Chlum.
The wind pump remained only a dysfunctional municipal symbol and a local rarity.
The dominant was put into operation at this year's meeting of natives.
It was not until 2008 that the Chlums decided to repair the wind wheel again and restart the operation.
They had a replica of the original wheel made - reduced by an average of half a meter.
The bike was mounted on a mast, but the same year it had to be brought down.
The replica manufacturer did not choose the appropriate material and the wheel could not resist wind gusts.
Then the chlum dominant rested for several years dismantled under the roof.
Since June this year, however, the round on the high mast is spinning again.
On the occasion of the meeting of the natives, the village had the replica of the bike modified and again put it on the top of the iron tower.
But the wheel draws utility water from the well only to the overflow blind shoulder.
And during the summer we completely disconnected it, because there was little water in the well.
It was at least empty.
"In the autumn, we will disconnect the shaft of the wind wheel from the pump in the suction basket again," Mayor Mašek explained.
Chlum is not the only municipality in the Czech Republic where the wind wheel got into the municipal emblem, but it is the only village of this kind in the whole Highlands.
In honor of local technical monuments, they have a similar element in honor of local technical monuments, for example, in Chvalkovice and Zelená Hora in the Vyškov region, in Kuzelov in the Hodonín region, Partutovice in the Přerov region or in the Police in the Vsetín region.
