After talks with his European colleagues, Interior Minister Milan Chovanec (ČSSD) complains that other states are pushing the Czech Republic to accept quotas for the redistribution of refugees, but reject any discussion.
He also points out that no one has yet explained to him how he should keep the allocated refugees in the Czech Republic if they do not want to live in our country anyway.
"We did not receive the answer and that is why we wanted the quotas to be deleted from the final text," Chovanec told reporters.
Can you describe more specifically the position you came up with at the meeting of the Ministers of the Interior and Foreign Affairs of the European Union?
We do not agree with mandatory quotas as a system that simply cannot work.
We can't talk about migrants as bags of salt or flour.
They're living beings who have some visions, they're going somewhere, they've got some relatives.
We wanted to hear from our colleagues how we are able to keep migrants in the territory of the Member States if they were redistributed.
We can't imagine.
We did not get a response and therefore we wanted the quotas to be deleted from the final text.
With other conclusions - functional hotspots, i.e. registration points, border protection, camps outside Europe, trust fund for African countries and other things, we have no problem with that.
We've been talking about this for a year now and saying this is the way.
But saying the quotas will solve everything?
We've been dealing with forty thousand not long ago, now it's a hundred and twenty thousand.
When will it be five hundred thousand?
And how do we keep these people in that territory?
Ninety-eight percent of all people who cross over us want to go to Germany.
Almost no one wants to come to us, we just don't know how to keep them here.
Other foreigners, Ukrainians, Vietnamese and others who take the Czech Republic as a destination country, are gaining asylum in our country, but the interest of people from this migration wave, i.e. from Syria and other countries, is limited to zero.
You mentioned that the refugees don't really want to come to us, but we've already committed to accept fifteen hundred people.
Wouldn't it be possible to accept more of them in this way?
We are committed to accepting 1500 people, but with a condition.
We said: functional hotspots, border protection, military operation.
Even with the 1500, the point is that there will be 1100 people with whom we will deal with the asylum procedure.
They'll come into our detention facility and we'll treat them the same way we did with the ones we've captured.
It is a big question, and we will debate this with Europe whether we can detain the people who will be registered in Italy and Greece, or Hungary.
Because Europe treats it in such a way that if they have a registration, they cannot be detained.
That is, they will come to our territory with registration, and if there is an agreement that is not yet, it may happen that even the 1100 will not be kept in the territory of the Czech Republic and they will leave for Germany again.
If we can detain them during the asylum procedure, we will handle the asylum procedure with them.
If it is Syria’s citizens, Eritrea, almost 98 percent of them are internationally protected, according to European statistics.
They will then be given documents that will allow them to travel around Europe.
And I think these people will end up in the target countries again.
Then there are four hundred people who will be resettled.
This is the second project that is still underway, and there we have only progressed in discussing with the churches the possibility that they could help them get employment, accommodation and so on.
But that's a run for a very long haul.
You said that at the ministerial meeting with us, the other states were not willing to discuss.
But isn’t it that the Czech Republic only rejects quotas, but does it not offer any solidarity step to unblock the discussion?
What exactly do you think this is a solidarity step?
If the Federal Republic of Germany says that all migrants from Syria can go to them, the news spreads in hours throughout all the camps around Europe, but also in Turkey, Jordan.
It encourages another migration wave that is going to Germany because they simply do not want to come to us.
We think that the way is to protect the external borders - simply to deter those migration waves, to help those in need, and to separate economic migrants.
Clearly let them know they don't stand a chance.
In the last year alone, fifty thousand Kosovons came to Germany.
From safe Kosovo, where we pay all the saturation of this state, including the police, the courts, the prosecutor's offices.
If we could separate them and not accept them or accept them only according to the needs of economies, the fifty percent of what social systems spend on them today could go to refugees.
Compared to the first day when Germany introduced controls, the number of detainees in the Czech Republic jumped.
It's now eighty, the first day it was twelve.
How far is it to go to make border controls even tighter?
We were afraid of being caught in the order of hundreds of people.
These are the numbers we can handle.
We still have several hundred vacancies in stone detention facilities.
Of course, all the people we hold back will be returning Austria within seven days.
We do it by default.
The Austrians are the only ones who take these people away from us, with Hungary it's complicated and the Greeks - that's a completely unnecessary story.
So where is the breaking point?
Would it have to be a thousand a day?
I think it would have to be several hundred a day.
Two hundred, three hundred people a day two, three consecutive days exhaust our capacities so much that crisis plans will come in.
Then I agree with the Prime Minister that he would immediately convene an emergency government.
He is very interested in the whole thing, we are in phone contact several times a day.
If the situation arises, the government can meet de facto immediately and by one resolution it would decide to strengthen the police for the army, let us give it a customs administration, or a prison service.
The extreme option is a state of emergency, which has now been declared by Hungary in some places?
I don't think we can get this far.
Remember that our position is different, we are a national state within Europe, we have a Schengen border only and only at the airport.
I don't know what would have to happen for this to happen on the territory of the Czech Republic, I don't want to spread alarm information.
All the information we have, whether from Moldova, Serbia, Hungary, suggests that the Hungarians will try to divert the migration flow to Croatia and Slovenia, which would then mean a direct trip to Austria.
The Czech Republic would be very marginally affected, almost at all.
