Speed on the highways will remain the same.
The acceleration to 150 km/h was rejected by the House.
On selected sections of motorways, it will not be possible to increase the maximum speed limit up to 150 km/h under favorable conditions.
On Tuesday, the House decided when it acceded to an amendment to the Senate, which rejected the speed increase.
The amendment to the Roads Act will now go to the president.
President Miloš Zeman said at the end of April that he would veto the law allowing a hundred and fifty-kilometre speed.
Transport Minister Dan Ťok (for ANO) was also opposed to the increase, according to which the Czech motorway network is not yet built for such a speed.
Ťok on Tuesday backed the Senate version of the bill before MPs.
The approved amendment will now allow, in line with the original government proposal, to increase the speed from 90 to 110 kilometers per hour on selected first-class roads, especially four-lane ones.
The Chamber of Deputies first extended this possibility to highways, on which it could be driven in selected sections at speeds of up to 150 km/h, but the Senate rejected it.
The MPs have now accepted his proposal.
Senators, with the consent of the Minister of Transport, also removed the authorization of the traffic police to have the last say in the regulation of local roads, which are taken care of by municipalities.
The Senate version, which was approved by the House, also provides that sewerage, water or public lighting cables can be stored longitudinally under the road surface.
Municipalities would save money on land purchases.
Municipalities should also not be obliged to take care of road vegetation along local roads, regardless of the owner of the relevant land.
The amendment is also intended to help improve road protection and facilitate the management of towed vehicles for municipalities, to which owners do not subscribe.
Newly, municipalities could sell towed vehicles, which their owners will not apply for within a six-month period after the towing notice.
Municipalities will have the possibility to exclude transit freight traffic through their territory on the roads of the second and third classes under the threat of a fine even for forwarding companies.
The amendment also abolishes the possibility of introducing electronic motorway signs instead of existing paper stamps, which will be used after 1 January next year.
According to the government, this will save money for the introduction of an electronic system.
