For slightly obese diabetics, weight loss surgery could be useful
The benefits of weight loss surgery for slightly obese people with type 2 diabetes can last at least five years, according to a new study.
However, it is still too early to say whether slightly obese people with type 2 diabetes live longer after weight loss surgery than those who are given non-surgical treatment.
"The mortality data lasts a long time to display," Dr. Robin Blackstone, a weight loss surgery expert who wrote an editorial on JAMA's new study of surgery.
Surgeries for weight loss, bariatric surgery use different methods to shrink the stomach.
Reduce hunger and limit the human body to absorb food.
Over the years, bariatric operations have proven effective for the treatment of type 2 diabetes, but most of the survey was conducted on people with morbid obesity with a body mass index (BMI) of 25 or higher.
BMI, which measures the weight relationship relative to height, is considered normal in values between 18.5 and 24.9.
BMI values of 25 or higher indicate overweight of a person, and people with a value above 30 are considered obese.
You can calculate your BMI here: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For their new studies, researchers at the General Min-Sheng Hospital in Taiwan have used data collected from a study since 2007, which deals with two types of bariatric surgery - gastric bypass and gastrectomy - in treatments for type 3 diabetes in people who were slightly obese.
The average BMI among those underwent surgery fell from 31 to 24.5 at the end of their fifth year, according to the study.
Meanwhile, the BMI of those who were not given surgical treatment for diabetes remained roughly the same at 29.
Among patients with surgery, diabetes was resolved entirely in 36 percent and partly in 28 cases.
In the drug-treated group, only 1 percent was completely resolved for diabetes comparison, and in part only in about 2 percent of patients.
Furthermore, control of blood pressure, triglycerides and "bad" LDL cholesterol was also demonstrated "generally better in the surgical group," the authors found.
The researchers also monitored the patient's level of hemoglobin A1c in the blood, which reflects the ongoing blood sugar levels in the body.
Hemoglobin A1c is best kept below 7 percent, according to researchers.
After the operation, the average hemoglobin A1c dropped from about 9 percent to about 6 percent.
In the drug-treated group, however, this value remained at about 8 percent.
But this better "glycemic control" - reflected in better levels of hemoglobin A1c - has not reduced the death rate at five years, according to chief researcher Dr. Chih-Cheng Hsu and his colleagues.
The research team also compared the average results with two types of operations.
After the fifth year, the group with bypass lost more weight compared to the group of gastrectomy (18.7 versus 14.2 kg), achieved greater BMI declines (7.4 against 5.1) and hemoglobin A1c (3.1 percent vs 2.1 percent) and were more likely to remise diabetes (46.9 percent versus 16.7 percent).
While the new study does not show an improvement in survival or surgery after five years, there is evidence from the study of stronger people in Sweden, where they found that surgery leads to life prolongation, says Blackstone of the University of Arizona College or Medicine-Phoenix.
According to a Swedish study, obese people who underwent bariatric surgery had about a 29 percent greater chance of survival over the next 15 years, compared to a group that tried more conventional methods.
Although the new study has not shown an improvement in survival among patients after surgery, according to Blackstone, this is a reassuring outcome for people with a BMI below 35 who are interested in these procedures.
"Right here, this work is critical because it states that surgery is safer in a lower BMI group," without increasing the risk of death or kidney disease, he states.
Blackstone also further argues that people and their doctors should start taking weight really seriously after a decrease in the patient's BMI between 27 and 30.
"I think we've been waiting too long with the fact that we're showing people the gravity of the situation," he says.
