Minister for Regional Development Karla Šlechtová (for ANO) pointed out that cases where insurance companies have not paid full compensation are not euro-comform.
She drew attention to this year's decision of the Constitutional Court, which confirmed that the client is entitled to a full refund regardless of the insurance limit.
Insurance companies will receive enough information about the management of travel agencies and will be able to determine the right limit, Šlechtová pointed out.
"We appreciate the effort to increase consumer protection, but it must have such a limit to be feasible," said Miroslav Kalousek, vice-chairman of TOP 09.
According to him, the bank guarantee will not work because no one will give it unlimited.
"Travel agencies will have to cease their activities or move abroad," Kalousek warned.
Tomio Okamura (SPD), a member of the Presidium of the Association of Czech Travel Agencies, disagreed with Kalousek’s concerns based on a survey of the CK members.
"Stop showing us the lobbying of insurance companies," he said.
The statement of insurance companies does not make Okamura relevant, there is no official written statement to that effect.
However, they are looking into whether travel agencies will make complicity, which is not a problem, according to Okamura.
Jana Fischerová (ODS), who referred to the opinion of the competing Association of Travel Agency of the Czech Republic, and her party colleague Petr Bendl, who spoke about the lubrication of stairs to Czech travel agencies, also warned against the provision.
According to Fischer, travel agencies will not be able to arrange insurance.
"Consumer protection is working," Fischer said.
Her motion to launch the disputed passage was not approved by the House.
Vojtěch Filip (KSČM) did not go to the committee because of the alleged violation of the Civil Code.
Philip drew attention to travel agencies, which he said could threaten consumers.
The rapporteur of the draft, Martina Berdychová (ANO), withdrew her proposal, in view of the verdict of the Constitutional Court, which would limit the liability of insurance companies in cases where they could not know that the insurance benefits would not cover the entire risk.
The amendment will not originally propose a minimum four-million-dollar insurance limit for travel agencies that offer air travel, and a million-dollar limit for offices selling, for example, bus tours.
The border will remain at 30 percent of planned sales from the sale of tours.
However, the limit of the insurance payment will have to be such that in the event of the insolvency of the travel agency it will cover all claims of customers.
Even after the modifications, the standard stipulates that travel agencies will have to newly indicate which travel agency organizes the trip for the tours sold.
Travel agencies will have to submit to insurance companies, among other things, data on the management and number of tours before the conclusion of the contract.
The approved amendment of the Public Administration Committee also provides for further regular information to insurance companies.
Travel agencies will have to provide them with daily data on the number of passengers and tours sold, the total price of the tours sold and the amount of deposits and sales for tours and vouchers for them.
If the Ministry of Regional Development finds that the travel agency has failed to fulfil any of the legal obligations to the insurance company, it will invite it, according to the draft, to remedy it or it will be able to prohibit it from entering into new contracts in the event that the breach of duty could jeopardize the interests of customers.
The amendment is also intended to newly adjust the financing of the mountain service.
The Ministry of Regional Development will determine the amount of the subsidy to the mountain service on the basis of its application, which it will always submit until the end of April for the next year.
The application will include a report on the use of state money last year, a financial spending plan and a forward-looking outlook for the next two years.
According to the association, however, the lawmaker did not think about the situation, what will happen if the insurance company terminates the contract.
It will not be allowed to organize tours and clients who bought the trip before the termination of insurance will lose it according to the association.
In this case, the CK will suffer a significant loss and may even go bankrupt, even though its management was in good shape.
One of the options for how travel agencies can cope with such a situation will be the action against the state for compensation.
Another option will be to go abroad and use much softer conditions abroad, and in our market we will only act as agencies, said the association's vice-chairman, Jan Pope.
According to him, the draft amendment also contains the institute of the bank guarantee, but so unsophisticated that it cannot be implemented in practice at all, because the bank guarantee cannot sound to an unlimited amount.
According to the association, the change in the current practice is de facto unnecessary.
In the light of the new EU directive, the whole law will have to be revised again in the next two years.
A total of 942 active insured travel agencies are currently operating on the Czech market.
Only three CKs have ceased their activities this year.
Domestic travel agencies sell tours worth about twenty billion CZK per year.
