Xi calls for the economy to open up to the wider world
It is necessary to open the economy to the wider world to boost growth, President Xi Jinping told the group whose job is Tuesday's governance reform.
"China should engage in attracting foreign investment and expertise and improving open policies," he said regarding the 16th session of the central head of the group on deepening overall reform.
Promoting the opening of the emerging reforms will add new impetus and vitality, it will also provide new space for economic growth, according to Xi.
The leading group has adopted a number of directives, including a negative list of regulatory market access, the loosening of border control policy, support for state-owned enterprises (SOEs) to absorb private capital and the reorganisation of the registration resident system.
The statement said a negative list will be drawn up identifying sectors and businesses that are outside the limits for investment.
This system will be gradually tested and improved through test programs.
The move is significant because it will give the market a greater role in allocating resources, ensuring a legal business environment and making the market more open, the statement said.
The government will also release controls on the powers it delegates to companies, and will make sure that the firms themselves decide how to manage their business.
The statement also said that China will allow border areas to discover new models of cross-border economic cooperation and new mechanisms for promoting regional growth.
In an effort to open up the state-controlled sector, more areas will be open to private investment.
"The government will not change its policy towards foreign investment and will protect the legal interests of companies that are funded from abroad and will provide them with better services," the statement said.
In addition, it will be easier for foreigners to apply for a permanent residence permit or a "green card," thanks to the optimization of requirements and simplifying the application process.
The provision of the rights of lawyers to practice and develop professional judges and prosecutors was also discussed at the meeting.
The meeting was also attended by Prime Minister Li Keqiang and leaders Liu Yunshan and Zhang Gaoli, according to a statement issued after the meeting.
New inpatient departments may be created in the Karlovy Vary Region.
According to Deputy Governor of the Karlovy Vary Region Jakub Pánik (ČSSD), the current capacity of the inpatient departments of two regional hospitals and two private hospitals in the region is sufficient and partial adjustments should be made on the basis of an agreement between the departments of individual hospitals.
There are also opportunities to expand care in the region.
For example, in the department of surgical departments, one-day surgery could be created, where according to the set concept, surgical procedures that do not require hospitalization longer than 24 hours would be performed.
In which particular hospitals the workplaces focused on one-day surgery should be, it is not yet clear.
The skin department of the Karlovy Vary Hospital could create a laser center with the possibility of using laser technology for skin diseases.
The concept also recommended the formation of an apalic center that would care for patients with brain involvement who are in a vegetative state.
Such a center should be established centrally and should be an integral part of the anesthesiology-resuscitation department.
There is also the possibility of concentrating such a facility in the hospital Ostrov, where similar care already exists.
Another inpatient capacity, which appears to be insufficient in the Karlovy Vary Region, are aftercare beds, especially beds of Long-Term Sick Care Centers (LDN), whose capacity in Nejdek is insufficient and, above all, should be closely connected to acute care beds.
Part of this facility should act as rehabilitation beds and part as classic LDN beds, recommends the concept.
As he points out, the aftercare beds are missing mainly in the hospital Karlovy Vary.
There, abandoned buildings could be used after centralization.
Last but not least, social health beds are absent in the Karlovy Vary Region with a focus on the treatment of Alzheimer’s disease.
These beds are scarce throughout the country, so it could also serve for other regions as the so-called Alzheimer Center.
Hospitals should also prepare for the introduction of so-called follow-up beds, for which funds of European subsidies will be released.
"These are beds that will be connected to the fields of supespecialized care and will form a space for the translation of patients after the procedure, for example after cardiac surgery, neurosurgical, transplantation or other intervention," describes the regional concept of inpatient care.
New services could also be offered in the field of psychiatric care.
